  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This activity is illegal in almost every country around the world because it enables criminals to profit from their illicit activities and undermines the integrity of financial systems.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **International Agreements**:  \n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental organization, sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Over 200 countries and jurisdictions have committed to these standards.  \n   - The **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)** and the **United Nations Convention against Corruption (UNCAC)** both include provisions criminalizing money laundering.\n\n2. **National Laws**:  \n   - Almost every country has enacted specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act** establish frameworks to combat money laundering.  \n     - In the **European Union**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** harmonize AML laws across member states.  \n     - Countries like the **UK**, **Canada**, **Australia**, and others have robust AML legislation in place.\n\n3. **Consequences**:  \n   - Money laundering is a criminal offense punishable by severe penalties, including fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and businesses that fail to comply with AML regulations can also face significant legal and financial consequences.\n\n4. **Global Enforcement**:  \n   - Governments and international organizations work together to detect, investigate, and prosecute money laundering activities. Cross-border cooperation is essential to combat this global issue.\n\n### Conclusion:\nMoney laundering is universally recognized as illegal, and there is a strong global framework in place to prevent and punish it. However, the effectiveness of enforcement varies by country, and challenges remain in combating increasingly sophisticated methods used by criminals.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
